04883nam a22006255i 9780889207202DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892072027 a10.51644/97808892072022doi  a(DE-B1597)667880  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43a791.4365205409711 aLow, Brian J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNFB Kids :bPortrayals of Children by the National Film Board of Canada, 1939-1989 /cBrian J. Low. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (294 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Childhood and Family in Canada00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tChildren in a Cinematic Society -- tEarly NFB Society: The Eyes of Democracy -- tLessons in Living: ‘‘Deconstruction’’ of a Rural Community in Early NFB Society -- tFields of Vision: Panoramas of Childhood in the Cinematic Society, 1947-67 -- t‘‘The New Generation’’: Mental Hygiene and the Portrayals of Children by the National Film Board of Canada, 1946-67 -- tA Progressive State of Disequilibrium: Social Relations in the Cinematic Society, 1968-89 -- tConclusion: The Century of the Cinematic Child -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix 1: 300 NFB Films with Significant Portrayals of Children and Youth, 1939-89 -- tAppendix 2: A Note Concerning the Process of Film Selection -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aImagine a society that exists solely in cinema — this book explores exactly that. Using a half-century of films from the archival collection of the National Film Board, NFB Kids: Portrayals of Children by the National Film Board of Canada, 1939-1989 overcomes a long-standing impasse about what films may be credibly said to document. Here they document not “reality,” but social images preserved over time — the “NFB Society” — an evolving, cinematic representation of Canadian families, schools and communities. During the postwar era, this society-in-cinema underwent a profound change in its child rearing and schooling philosophies, embracing “modern” notions based upon principles espoused by the American mental hygiene movement. Soon after the introduction of these psychological principles into NFB homes in 1946 and schools in 1956, there was a subtle transformation in adult-child relations, which progressively, over time, narrowed the gulf of power between generations and diminished the socializing roles of the NFB parents and teachers. NFB Kids is a pioneering study within a new field of academic research — “cinema ethnography.” It adds to the growing body of knowledge about the function, and the considerable impact of, psychiatry and psychology in the post-war social reconstruction of Canadian society and social history. It will be of interest to academics over a broad spectrum of disciplines and to anyone thinking about the advancing arbitrary power of the cinematic state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren in motion picturesxHistory. 0aMotion picturesxHistoryxCanada. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectsxCanada. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aMotion pictureszCanadaxHistory. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEthnography. 4aFilm & Media. 4aHistory. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aSocial Science: Sociology. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920720240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978088920720